WELCOME TO OPEN MIC 101! 

***

Consider this post your one stop shop for any Grizzly related questions! This post includes our rules, our layout, our location, our start time, and a handy guide on what to bring with you! Plus, a sneaky meet the hosts fitting in right at the end. 

***

Our rules are simple! No hate speech, trigger warn your poetry, keep your slot to four minutes or less, support others, listen respectfully, and clap loudly at the end of poems!
*
Our layout is simple! We begin at eight pm, and we randomly select five open mic-ers names from our magical hat. After they have performed, we have a short break, and we rinse and repeat. After our final five slots, our fantastic headliner - whoever they may be - takes the stage to close the night!
*
What to bring is simple! Government issued photo-ID is a requirement - we're held in Circo, which is a bar in Selly Oak, so you need to be eighteen to enter. If you're a student, bring your student-ID along too. You'll also need Â£3-Â£5 in cash, Â£3 for students, Â£5 for non students. This is annoying, we know, but there is a cashpoint really nearby. 

***

We hope this handy guide helps make your Grizzly experience Pear-fect in every way! Izzie and Q look forward to meeting you at the next open mic!

In a major step toward fulfilling its student welfare manifesto, the Indian National Studentsâ€™ Organization (INSO) has donated gym equipment to three girlsâ€™ hostels (GH 04, 07, 10) and three boysâ€™ hostels (BH 01, 02, 04) at Panjab University. The initiative, promised by Ex-National President Sh. Digvijay Chautala, aims to promote fitness, physical health, and mental well-being among students.

The effort was led by PUCSC Secretary Vineet Yadav, This year candidate Vishesh Dhaka, INSO President Jashan Saini, and Chairman Anirudh Malhan. INSO leaders stated that creating accessible wellness facilities is a key priority for the party.

The gym equipment was handed over in the presence of student leaders Jashan Saini, Anirudh Malhan, Aryan Saharan, Vishesh Dhaka, Gagandeep Lohan (Khanda Kheri), Keshav Raval, Krish Asija, Supreet Malik, Sahil Sheokand, Manmeet Siwach, Veeram Chauhan, Dhairya Gupta, Dinesh Srivastav, Kinshuk, Anuj Malik, Vansh, Anni Nain, Yash Raj, Ritik Yadav, Gumaan, Aadarsh and Armaan Chahal.

We are excited to share the latest findings from our Erasmus+ project, "Insects Innovation in Gastronomy." 

The research explores the potential of insects as a sustainable protein source and focuses on attitudes toward insect consumption across multiple European countries, including Spain, Italy, Turkey, Cyprus, Greece, and Romania. 

Key Highlights:
ğŸ”¸ Consumer Insights: We surveyed chefs, professionals in hospitality (HoReCa), and consumers to understand readiness for insect consumption.
ğŸ”¸ Food neophobia: Addressing challenges like food neophobia and cultural barriers to accepting insects as food.
ğŸ”¸ Nutritional Benefits: Examining the awareness of insects' nutritional value and environmental impact.

Desk Research Insights:
â–¶ï¸ Historical Context: Exploring cultural traditions surrounding insect consumption across Europe.
â–¶ï¸ Technological Innovations: Reviewing insect farming and processing advancements.
â–¶ï¸ Regulatory Landscape: Analyzing EU policies on food safety, labeling, and marketing of insect-based food.

The findings will guide strategies to introduce insects into European markets, promoting them as a sustainable and nutritious protein alternative. Explore the full report on our website.

Day 6 was all about sounds music, nature, our voices, the beats and rhythms our bodies can make, and the noises of each other and the world around us ğŸ¶.

It marked the close of Act 2 of our time here in Ommen, a chapter of creating, exploring different artforms, mediums, and activating. 

We started with a walk to the Sahara, letting the journey be part of the exploration. On the way, we played while listening, sharing and thinking about our connection to music and the art of sound.

When we got there, we walked, listened, and made noises to explore what is there for us with both the world around us and each other. Soon our jam session started, mixing natural sounds, instruments, voices and our own rhythms.

Later, we got into recording and playing with radio theatre, telling our own stories of queer joy ğŸ“».

To close the day, we sat together and shared gratitude for the journey so far, for the connections and community weâ€™ve built, and for the queer art and queer spaces weâ€™ve claimed. We leave this chapter feeling full of love, of creativity, of the belief that art and each other can carry us forward ğŸ³ï¸â€ğŸŒˆğŸ³ï¸â€âš§ï¸.

When the internet disappears, the story begins.
This time, our main character is Marinela, a 20-year-old girl from Kazakhstan living in Jamaica, who finds herself in the middle of a storm with no electricity, no WiFi, and no digital distractions.

What would you do?

Marinela cleaned, walked around her neighborhood, read a book, and ended up writing a poemâ€¦ just maybe a little bit different than you would imagine. Her story became a comic during the What If? Youth Exchange, a reminder that sometimes, no WiFi means the best stories.

Studyabroadfriends is based on the idea of helping students who are going abroad to the same Erasmus city connect before arriving in their new city, through the concept: ğŸ“² Tag us â€“ we repost â€“ you connect.
The idea came from our own experiences studying abroad. Moving to a new city can be exciting, but those first days can also feel lonely; exploring the city for the first time alone, drinking your first coffee alone, and wishing you already had someone to share it with.
Thatâ€™s where studyabroadfriends comes in. Our goal is to help students connect in advance; ideally, even before boarding the plane. This way, you can already share the excitement, talk about your plans for the first week, and maybe you get along so well that you decide to move into a shared flat together!
So, if you're going abroad for a semester soon, follow this page and connect with people heading to the same city.
Thatâ€™s the idea behind studyabroadfriends: to help you meet great people before day one.

To beat this adjustment, or other similar changes, Iâ€™d definitely recommend a few quick tipsâ€¦

1. Keep an open conversation. Whether that be with your roommates, your advisors, your people at home or people here, make sure to not bottle up your feelings. Itâ€™s normal to feel sad, anxious, scared, happy, and everything in between - so let yourself feel those feelings!

2. Take some alone time. I know itâ€™s hard if you share a room or are exploring a brand new place, but take that time to explore on your own, journal out your feelings, take a longer shower than usualâ€¦ whatever you need.

3. Try your best to get into some sort of normal routine. Whether that be attempting a normal sleep schedule, working out how you normally do, or prioritizing your meals, a routine makes the transition feel a lot less overwhelming. Do your best to create some normalcy in a world full of change.

4. Enjoy it!!!! Things are going to be different and THAT IS OK. Allow yourself to try new things & donâ€™t compare your â€œnew lifeâ€ toooooo much to life at home, because naturally, theyâ€™re never going to be the same.

Expat friendship is basically mum-Tinder.
You matchâ€¦ you meetâ€¦ and then you go home and overthink every word you said ğŸ™ƒ

Sometimes itâ€™s awkward. Sometimes the vibe is off.
Other times itâ€™s effortless â€” like youâ€™ve known each other for years.

But just like dating, it takes a few â€œmehâ€ connections, a couple of dry chats, and maybe even a ghosting or twoâ€¦ before you find your people.

The ones who get it.
The friends whoâ€™ll text back, whoâ€™ll say â€œcome over, donâ€™t worry about the mess.â€
The ones who feel like family even if youâ€™ve only known them a few months.

So if youâ€™re still swiping through the friendship pool, hang in there.
There are people out there who will love you for your weird, your tired, your leggings and all.

#MovingToDubai #DubaiFriends #ExpatLifeDubai #NewInDubai #DubaiCommunity #mumindubai #DubaiMeetup #DubaiSupport #dubaiexpatslife #MakingFriendsAbroad #dubaidiaries #BritishInDubai #DubaiLife  #LivingOverseas

It can be daunting landing in a new country and not knowing anyone. You're not alone in that feeling (so many of us have been there). We get it. ğŸ¥º

The good news? Making connections in a new place can be one of the most rewarding parts of the journey. ğŸŒŸ

Here are some gentle, genuine tips to help you find your people:

ğŸ§© Join local groups or clubs
Look for meetup groups, sports teams, hobby circles, or language exchanges. Platforms like Meetup, Facebook groups, or even Discord servers for locals and expats can be great places to start.

ğŸ¨ Take a class
Sign up for yoga, cooking, art, or dance classes. Shared activities give you a natural way to meet people and start conversations.

ğŸ«¶ğŸ» Say yes to invitations
Even if you're unsure or feel out of your element, showing up matters. Dinners, festivals, small hangouts - they often lead to unexpected connections.

ğŸ“± Try friendship and event apps
Some apps that help you meet new people:
Bumble BFF - for making platonic friends
Meetup - for finding interest-based events

ğŸ‰ Go to cultural or community events
Attend local holidays, food markets, concerts, or public celebrations. They're often full of relaxed, curious people - the perfect setting for meeting someone new!

â³ Be patient
Real friendships take time. Just keep showing up, being kind, and staying open. The right people tend to show up when you're consistently around.

Making Friends in Germany: A Journey Worth Taking

Moving from India to Germany opens the door to a completely different social world. Itâ€™s excitingâ€”but letâ€™s be honest, it comes with challenges, especially when it comes to building meaningful friendships.

German communication is often very direct. Itâ€™s not meant to be unfriendlyâ€”itâ€™s simply about clarity. Once you understand this cultural nuance, it becomes much easier to connect and feel included.

Here are some practical ways to grow your social circle in Germany:
 â€¢ Join local clubs (Vereine): Whether itâ€™s sports, music, or volunteering, this is where many friendships begin.
 â€¢ Language meetups: Practice German and connect with others who are also navigating a new country.
 â€¢ Attend festivals and community events: Local markets and cultural fairs are great places to meet people and understand German life.
 â€¢ Use your work or university network: Small conversations can grow into lasting bonds.
 â€¢ Stay open and approachable: Friendships in Germany may take time to build, but theyâ€™re often strong and lasting.
 â€¢ Join expat and Indo-German communities: These spaces offer support, understanding, and opportunities to connect across cultures.

Settling into a new country takes timeâ€”but with patience and openness, youâ€™ll find your circle.

What is the International Student Meet Up? ğŸ¤”

Join us every Thursday evening to make new friends, share experiences, and build a strong international student community. Together, we'll create lasting memories and support each other's journey in the UK! 

The "International Students Meet-Up" is a series of events that caters to the needs of international students who might have missed out on the International Welcome Week.

This initiative is not just a collection of events but a cohesive platform that fosters community-building, provides crucial information, and offers a warm welcome to international students from diverse backgrounds.

At IIT Hyderabad's International Relations Cell, we believe that diversity is not just about where you come from but about where we're all going together. That's why we recently organized a fantastic meet-up for all our international students on campus!

Together, we'll make IIT Hyderabad not just a place for academic growth but also a hub for cultural exchange and global understanding.

It's great to celebrate along the way as you are able to maintain your habit. Maybe after 2 weeks, 1 month and beyond you can celebrate your progress in building and maintaining a new habit.â 
.â 
We hope that you have learnt something new to help you with creating new habits and keeping them up. Let us know in the comments what new habit you are hoping to start.â

Podcasts are becoming more and more popular with English learners. You can not only improve your English but also learn something about topics that you're interested in. Some other benefits of podcasts are: you'll improve your confidence when it comes to understanding native and non-native speakers, you'll improve your pronunciation and you can listen anytime and anywhere.
One podcast that's especially for English learners is @podcastyoudontsay where you can hear all about life around the world, cultural differences and travel experiences.

As you work towards completing your goal, it's great to celebrate the little achievements along the way. This can be a great boost to your confidence and will allow you feel a sense of achievement. â 
.â 
A good way to approach this is to reward yourself after completing the smaller tasks that lead up to the big goal that you set yourself. Maybe it's making your favourite hot drink or going to the cinema. Celebrate however you like!â 
.â 
That's the last of our "How to set good goals" posts. We hope that you have learnt something new about goal setting. If you want to share your goals, let us know in the comments.â

Our second tip for setting good goals, is to make sure to set an achievable deadline.â 
ğŸ“…â 
Setting a deadline means that you have an end date to work towards and it can help you stay focused. It also means that you can set smaller tasks with dates that lead up to your big deadline.â 
ğŸ“…â 
Try and be specific with your dates, for example would be: "I want to achieve this goal by at least 31st October 2020."â

This week we are going to be looking our how you can set and achieve goals in work and study. â 
â¬‡â 
Our first tip is to be specific about what it is you want to achieve. The more specific you are, the more likely you will be able to measure your progress. For example a bad example of a non-specific goal would be: "I want get better at English." â 
A better and more specific example would be: "I want to be able to have a conversation in English for 20 minutes without needing to use Google Translate." â 
â¬‡â 
Once you have figured out your specific goal, make sure to write it down so that you can reflect on it regularly. â 
â¬‡â 
Check back on Wednesday for our second post about setting good goals.â

One of the best countries to travel if you are tight on pennies but still want to experience all the country has to offer! 

ğŸ  Accommodation: $15-$20/night. As a couple we stayed in hostels or homestays in private rooms as they were often cheaper than 2 dorm beds. These accomodations are usually ran by locals and are honestly amazing. We booked through booking.com and made sure they had good reviews. 

ğŸ”ï¸Activities: $20-$30/activity. The most popular thing to do in Peru is hike, which you can do for free. However sometimes itâ€™s easiest and cheapest to book a tour for the transport (they still let you hike alone). We booked many tours through GetYourGuide for very affordable prices. There are so many companies so you donâ€™t need to book in advance. 

ğŸ£Food: $10-15/day. Eat locally and from street vendors!!! The food in Peru is amazing. We ate from the markets/street every day and had no issues with food poisoning. The ceviche is to die for. 

ğŸšInternal Travel: $10-$30/journey. The price depends on how long the journey is. You can book all your buses through redBus Peru online. It is simple and easy. The buses are comfortable and generally on time. No need to book far in advance, 1-4days is fine.

After graduating, I moved to Perpignan with the Teaching Assistant Program in France. This bustling village provided a respite from a lifetime of hustle. It sloweeed things down and allowed me to recenter and reconnect.

The experience was lovely and often lonely. A couple weeks after I arrived, the g*n*c*de began, and I spent much of my time online, desperate to connect with people who were as enraged and heartbroken as I.

Although locals were intrigued by me, there was little effort to integrate me into their established social circles. Without a car I was relatively stuck, and it took about 8 months to stop feeling like every interaction is French wasnâ€™t a mental task.

Despite the loneliness, I felt years of built up anxiety and the alarm of an internal clock dissipate. My position in the world became more clear and grounded. My love for myself and others grew more flexible and sound. I was living in a beautiful part of the world, and I relearned that there is magic everywhere when you know how to see it. 

I, an immigrant by choice and with citizenship, could not compare my struggles to many of the immigrants I befriended. I am humbled by their experiences, and grateful for their generosity with me.
They were a majority of my most meaningful connections. Moroccans, Spaniards, Algerians, and Senegalese embraced me, and together we explored the region and took on French bureaucracy and arrogance.

I want to thank the people who eased this transition for me. The ones who made linguistic barriers disappear, made me feel like my accent was colorful and endearing, and that I was always understood.

Who oriented their schedules to ensure I always had a ride when needed, and delivered dinners and toilet paper to my doorstep on Sundays when I forgot stores were closed.

Who drove me to the mountains and beach concaves when I craved the touch of nature. Who found joy in times shared together.

âœ… Ngo's with common goals have drafted projects in the fields that compete most with them, ngo's with different goals found a way to dialogue on unfamiliar topics with the aim of making the most of their potential.

âœ… We have also discussed those problems that unfortunately occur in the implementation and management of Erasmus projects and, on a daily basis, in youth communities. Alcoholism, mental health, community integration. All topics to which we sought common and effective solutions.

THE GOLDEN CITY HOTEL - BALLARAT,VICTORIA.

Established in 1856 as the Adelphi Hotel and occupying a prominent corner position opposite St Patrickâ€™s Cathedral is the Golden City Hotel.A 1900 alteration saw the addition of a verandah and the adoption of its current name to what we see today.
This is a pub that opens early for breakfast.And as it was a little early to enjoy a beer,I decided to enjoy a mug of mocha.The breakfast menu is large and includes my favourite option of Eggs Benedict.Both the lunch and dinner menus are huge with many pub classics,pasta,steaks,and Asian dishes with vegan options available,all of which can be enjoyed in the main dining area on the ground floor.And for large functions thereâ€™s the airy Atrium Room and upstairs you have the Balcony Room.
Adjacent to the cafÃ© side of the pub are the four taps of mainstream beers plus a ginger beer and lemon squash.
Finally,thank you to Dee and Lecey for the great service.

Enjoy.CheersğŸº.

Come on in to Monroe's Tavern on the 29th of August to catch Federica & Lorcan performing on our stage from 7:30-9:30 p.m. on Friday night ğŸ§¡ 

Federica Fruscella is an Italian born independent artist, singer and composer based in Dublin. Her creative world revolves around music, theatre, translation and a deep interest in psyche and folktales, finding its roots in a family tradition of storytelling. Through the years, she has focused her musical research on unreleased melodies both from the Celtic world and the Mediterranean area. She recently released her first solo album inspired by Celtic folklore, and her beautifully expressive voice lends a warm Mediterranean flavor to the Celtic songs.

Lorcan has been performing live and recording for almost twenty years with various acts and in numerous styles, in places as diverse as New York, Australia, the UK, and continental Europe. After years of travel and self-discovery, Lorcan returned to Ireland in 2020 to pursue a career playing and teaching music. Lorcan holds a diploma in professional musicianship from BIMM Dublin, and is a versatile guitarist and a seasoned entertainer who enjoys performing in different styles.

We can't wait!

caption:
A pub crawl is not only about the beers but meeting the locals.

Peter at The Mauldons Brewery Tap took a shine to my @prancingponybrewery cap and tshirt. Got chatting about local beers, the Australian craft beer scene and even McLaren Vale wine region.

Then got back to drinking. 

The â€œBlack Adderâ€ Stout, at 5.3%, was a warm, smooth and flavoursome brew. A rich dark colour, this settles down with zero head and chocolatey aromatic notes. Good level of bitterness, blended with vibes of roasted nut, gives this a dry sensation. Fruity notes and splash of cocoa delivers a slightly smooth, chocolatey mouthfeel that lingers on the tongue throughout.

A huge dark roasty beer and a great local bloke!

ğŸŒğŸƒ Barcelona | 12.2024 ğŸ‡ªğŸ‡¸ 

I come from Brittany, in France.

I was born and grew up there before moving to Nantes for my studies.

In 2003, I discovered KrakÃ³w as an Erasmus student.

Since then, I have been living and developing my companies in my beloved city. 

I come back to Brittany in general every 2 years for Christmas time. 

For a long time, I was used to flying from Krakow to Paris and then to go by train from Paris to my home town there. 

Nevertheless, over the past few years, we usually fly from Krakow to somewhere in Southern Europe (Italy, Portugal, or Spain for now) to spend a few days there and then fly on to Nantes.

Last time, we chose Barcelona and it was definitely a very good choice. 

The weather was amazing for winter time. 

It was not my 1st stay in the capital of Catalonia. Anyway, it is always a good idea to experience Barcelona at its best. There are so many beautiful places to visit and things to do there.
